u survey conducted among employers in Russia, it turned out that over the year the number of companies that are ready to consider and hire junior (beginner) IT specialists has increased','<div>As part of the hh.ru survey conducted among Russian employers, it turned out that over the year the number of companies that are ready to consider and hire junior (beginner) IT specialists who have only online IT courses in the education base has increased. Which IT specialists are most in demand among Russian businesses, how great are the chances of finding a job without a specialized IT education, are employers willing to pay extra for brains, and also why IT specialists get rejected - in the hh.ru study. The survey was conducted from May 10 to June 2, 2023. Hi-Tech tells the main thing.</div><div><br></div><div>A survey of employers showed that at the moment the most demanded IT specialists among Russian employers from various industries are developers (63% of respondents), system engineers (42%), and technical support specialists (31%). Least of all, employers mentioned IT methodologists, data scientists and BI analysts as in-demand - these professions scored less than 1% of responses.</div><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://demo.butterflycms.com/uploads/media/2023/07/image.png\"></div><div>At the same time, in addition to specialization, the professional qualities of IT applicants are also important for employers. The top 3 in terms of importance in the selection of candidates included knowledge of the technology stack (this parameter is necessary for every second (53%) company hiring IT specialists), experience in the required position/specialty (49%), as well as the presence of successful and real cases in IT sphere (this parameter is important for 43% of employers). We evaluated companies and other indicators of IT applicants. Thus, for 43% of companies it is important that candidates adequately assess their salary requirements and not overstate them. The desired work schedule and employment format of a candidate can be the reason for refusal or, conversely, hiring for 34% of companies. But knowledge of English for an IT specialist is important only for 9% of the surveyed employers. Only 5% of companies pay serious attention to the candidate\'s age when hiring.<br></div>div style=\"text-align: center;\"&gt;<img src=\"https://demo.butterflycms.com/uploads/media/2023/07/image-2.png\"><div><div>Continuing the theme of work experience for IT applicants: 77% of company representatives said in the course of the survey that at the moment they prioritize candidates with experience in the IT field from 3 to 6 years. Another 66% of respondents noted that they are looking for even more experienced IT professionals with more than 6 years of experience. But juniors with experience from 1 to 3 years are ready to consider for employment only every third company (29%). Completely inexperienced IT candidates can be in demand in only 8% of companies in the labor market.</div><div>In this case, the decision of employers to give preference to candidates with experience in implementing any IT projects or orders is easy to understand. In difficult market conditions, when changes occur extremely quickly, companies cannot afford long-term onboarding of newcomers without experience, their training and mentoring. Now business relies on experienced, independent and fast-learning specialists who can not only quickly join the team, but also bring new projects, contacts, connections and best practices for the development of the company.</div></div><div><div><br></div><h3>Why companies refuse IT specialists to work</h3><div>Employers also named the reasons why they most often refuse employment to IT candidates. The leading reason is the discrepancy between salary offers and the expectations of the applicant (most often overstated). This was stated by 82% of employers. Due to insufficient experience in the IT profession, 52% of employers may refuse. Exactly the same number most likely will not cooperate with applicants who are outside the Russian Federation. Interestingly, failure to complete a test task by a candidate can be a reason for refusal in 46% of companies. But the lack of specialized IT education is the cause of failed employment in only 18% of cases.</div></div><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://demo.butterflycms.com/uploads/media/2023/07/image-1.png\"></div><div><h3>The Importance of IT Education</h3><div>Continuing the theme of specialized education in the IT field: 45% of business respondents said that university IT education is quite important for them. At the same time, they are ready to consider candidates without a tower, but with experience in the IT field or successful cases. At the same time, every fifth company (22%) noted that the candidate has a higher priority in terms of technical education and experience in the IT field than specialized higher IT education.</div><div>A survey of Russian employers also showed that the chances of finding a job for novice specialists who have only online courses in the background without successfully implemented cases, projects and ideas are quite small. Thus, more than 49% of interviewed employers hiring IT professionals said that their companies do not employ juniors who only have online courses in the database without any tangible practice, internship or experience. 35% are willing to consider inexperienced candidates. The rest of the survey participants found it difficult to answer.</div><div><br></div><div>At the same time, over the year, many companies have changed their attitude towards juniors who have only online courses behind them. Thus, the number of companies ready to hire novice IT specialists who have only completed training courses increased by 19 p.p. (from 16% to 35%).</div></div><div><h3>Brain Surcharge</h3><div>Another important point for understanding the labor market is the willingness of employers to pay salaries above the market average to employees who have the skills and competencies necessary for the company. The study shows that every tenth company surveyed (13%) has introduced a mechanism for additional payment for knowledge and competencies for in-demand specialists. Another 43% of Russian employers have the same practice. True, such privileges do not apply to all specialties, as a rule, engineering, digital and work areas. Meanwhile, over the year, the number of companies practicing such surcharges decreased by 13%. And at the same time, over the year, there have been more employers who are generally aware of this format of encouraging highly qualified specialists, but are not yet planning such a thing (growth by 19 p.p. from 13% in 2022 to 32% in 2023).</div><div>Source: hightech.fm</div></div>','Which IT professionals are in demand in 2023 and why','As part of the hh.ru survey conducted among employers in Russia, it turned out that over the year the number of companies that are ready to consider and hire junior (beginner) IT specialists has increased','work, work in IT',1,1,1,1,1,'en-US','2023-07-14 10:04:18',100,'2023-07-14 10:04:18',100),(8,6,' -   2023   ','aki-it-fahivci-potribni-v-2023-roci-i-comu','img_8462.jpg','   hh.ru     \',      ,       - junior ()','<p>   hh.ru     \',      ,       junior () -,        -.  -     ,        -,      ,          hh.ru.    10   2  2023 .   .</p><p>  ,       -         (63% ),   (42%),     (31%).      -, -  BI-      1% .</p><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://demo.butterflycms.com/uploads/media/2023/07/image.png\"></div><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><br></div>          -.  -3          (      (53%)   ),    / (49%),         -  (    43% ).      -. ,  43%  ,           .            , ,     34% .           9%  .          5% .<br><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><img src=\"https://demo.butterflycms.com/uploads/media/2023/07/image-2.png\"></div><div style=\"text-align: center;\"><br></div><div>     -: 